[{"data":1,"prerenderedAt":868},["ShallowReactive",2],{"header-locale:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F":3,"page:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F":4,"alt:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F":3,"prev-next:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F":843,"related:\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F":852},"\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F20190518\u002F1998986181\u002F",{"id":5,"title":6,"abbrlink":7,"altUrl":3,"body":8,"category":827,"date":828,"description":829,"extension":830,"lang":831,"meta":832,"navigation":313,"path":833,"readingMinutes":834,"seo":835,"standalone":836,"stem":837,"tags":838,"tldr":840,"updated":828,"url":841,"__hash__":842},"content\u002Fen\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions.md","[JS Weird World] No.27 Function Statements vs Function Expressions","1000150464",{"type":9,"value":10,"toc":819},"minimark",[11,16,20,24,30,41,44,67,78,81,101,122,128,132,135,182,191,229,232,242,246,249,283,290,297,341,345,348,384,387,390,393,405,408,411,498,504,513,516,519,530,573,576,581,591,594,640,655,665,672,675,739,745,803,807,815],[12,13,15],"h2",{"id":14},"intro","Intro",[17,18,19],"p",{},"Last chapter we figured out that functions are just objects. From here on, we're going to use that idea to do some genuinely fun and powerful stuff. But before we get there, we need to understand the difference between function statements and function expressions.",[12,21,23],{"id":22},"expressions","Expressions",[17,25,26],{},[27,28],"img",{"alt":23,"src":29},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002F9VZEr7V.png",[17,31,32,33,37,38],{},"An ",[34,35,36],"strong",{},"expression"," is a chunk of code that returns a value when you run it. In short: ",[34,39,40],{},"if a piece of code returns a value when you type it, it's an expression.",[17,42,43],{},"Let's look at some example code.",[45,46,51],"pre",{"className":47,"code":48,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"language-js shiki shiki-themes github-dark-high-contrast","var a\n","js","",[52,53,54],"code",{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,56,59,63],"span",{"class":57,"line":58},"line",1,[55,60,62],{"class":61},"sWyjQ","var",[55,64,66],{"class":65},"sMAXC"," a\n",[17,68,69,70,73,74,77],{},"That's it. Now open your browser, hit F12 to open the dev tools, and type ",[52,71,72],{},"console.log(a)",". You'll see that ",[52,75,76],{},"a"," is currently sitting in memory.",[17,79,80],{},"So what exactly is an expression? An expression returns a value. So when you type this:",[45,82,84],{"className":47,"code":83,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"a = 3;\n",[52,85,86],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,87,88,91,94,98],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,89,90],{"class":65},"a ",[55,92,93],{"class":61},"=",[55,95,97],{"class":96},"sCcAr"," 3",[55,99,100],{"class":65},";\n",[17,102,103,104,107,108,110,111,113,114,117,118,121],{},"Remember, the thing in the middle is an assignment operator. It assigns ",[52,105,106],{},"3"," to ",[52,109,76],{}," and then returns a value — so you get a value back, which is ",[52,112,106],{},". That behavior is an expression. Which also means the earlier ",[52,115,116],{},"var a"," actually returned a value too — that value was ",[52,119,120],{},"undefined",".",[17,123,124],{},[27,125],{"alt":126,"src":127},"Assignment operator","https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FxVhuw2H.png",[12,129,131],{"id":130},"statements","Statements",[17,133,134],{},"So what about statements? Take a look at this example. ↓",[45,136,138],{"className":47,"code":137,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"if (a === 3) {\n console.log('Hello');\n}\n",[52,139,140,156,176],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,141,142,145,148,151,153],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,143,144],{"class":61},"if",[55,146,147],{"class":65}," (a ",[55,149,150],{"class":61},"===",[55,152,97],{"class":96},[55,154,155],{"class":65},") {\n",[55,157,159,162,166,169,173],{"class":57,"line":158},2,[55,160,161],{"class":65}," console.",[55,163,165],{"class":164},"sj_SG","log",[55,167,168],{"class":65},"(",[55,170,172],{"class":171},"sTRMh","'Hello'",[55,174,175],{"class":65},");\n",[55,177,179],{"class":57,"line":178},3,[55,180,181],{"class":65},"}\n",[17,183,184,187,188,190],{},[52,185,186],{},"a === 3"," is actually an expression too, because it returns a value directly (either true or false). But the ",[52,189,144],{}," instruction is different — it's a statement. It doesn't return a value, so we can't assign it to a variable.",[45,192,194],{"className":47,"code":193,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"var b = if (a === 3) {\n  console.log('Hello');\n}\n",[52,195,196,216,225],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,197,198,200,203,205,208,210,212,214],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,199,62],{"class":61},[55,201,202],{"class":65}," b ",[55,204,93],{"class":61},[55,206,207],{"class":164}," if",[55,209,147],{"class":65},[55,211,150],{"class":61},[55,213,97],{"class":96},[55,215,155],{"class":65},[55,217,218,221,223],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,219,220],{"class":65},"  console.log(",[55,222,172],{"class":171},[55,224,175],{"class":65},[55,226,227],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,228,181],{"class":65},[17,230,231],{},"Here's the concept to take away:",[233,234,235,239],"ul",{},[236,237,238],"li",{},"A function expression returns a value directly.",[236,240,241],{},"A function statement doesn't return a value — it does something else instead.",[12,243,245],{"id":244},"function-statements","Function statements",[17,247,248],{},"In JavaScript we already know a function is an object, and inside functions we've got function statements and function expressions. These two are super powerful. Let's start by writing a function statement. ↓",[45,250,252],{"className":47,"code":251,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"function greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n",[52,253,254,265,278],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,255,256,259,262],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,257,258],{"class":61},"function",[55,260,261],{"class":164}," greet",[55,263,264],{"class":65},"() {\n",[55,266,267,269,271,273,276],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,268,161],{"class":65},[55,270,165],{"class":164},[55,272,168],{"class":65},[55,274,275],{"class":171},"'hi'",[55,277,175],{"class":65},[55,279,280],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,281,282],{"class":65},"};\n",[17,284,285,286,289],{},"When this runs, it doesn't return any value (and \"runs\" here doesn't mean ",[52,287,288],{},"greet()"," — it means the global execution context being created). The key trait of a function statement is hoisting: it gets stored in memory first, and stays there until you actually call the function.",[17,291,292,293,296],{},"We covered hoisting for variables and functions in an earlier chapter, so you can call ",[52,294,295],{},"greet"," before the function statement.",[45,298,300],{"className":47,"code":299,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"greet();\n\nfunction greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n",[52,301,302,309,315,323,336],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,303,304,306],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,305,295],{"class":164},[55,307,308],{"class":65},"();\n",[55,310,311],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,312,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},true,"\n",[55,316,317,319,321],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,318,258],{"class":61},[55,320,261],{"class":164},[55,322,264],{"class":65},[55,324,326,328,330,332,334],{"class":57,"line":325},4,[55,327,161],{"class":65},[55,329,165],{"class":164},[55,331,168],{"class":65},[55,333,275],{"class":171},[55,335,175],{"class":65},[55,337,339],{"class":57,"line":338},5,[55,340,282],{"class":65},[12,342,344],{"id":343},"function-expressions","Function expressions",[17,346,347],{},"Next up is the function expression.",[45,349,351],{"className":47,"code":350,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"var anonymousGreet = function() {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n",[52,352,353,368,380],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,354,355,357,360,363,366],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,356,62],{"class":61},[55,358,359],{"class":164}," anonymousGreet",[55,361,362],{"class":61}," =",[55,364,365],{"class":61}," function",[55,367,264],{"class":65},[55,369,370,372,374,376,378],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,371,161],{"class":65},[55,373,165],{"class":164},[55,375,168],{"class":65},[55,377,275],{"class":171},[55,379,175],{"class":65},[55,381,382],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,383,282],{"class":65},[17,385,386],{},"The thing to keep in mind here is \"a function is an object\" (and by the way, this is what people call an anonymous function).",[17,388,389],{},"(An anonymous function is just a function with no name.)",[17,391,392],{},"So how do you trigger this function expression?",[45,394,396],{"className":47,"code":395,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"anonymousGreet();\n",[52,397,398],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,399,400,403],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,401,402],{"class":164},"anonymousGreet",[55,404,308],{"class":65},[17,406,407],{},"That's a function expression. Feels pretty similar to a function statement, right?",[17,409,410],{},"Let's put both pieces of code together. ↓",[45,412,414],{"className":47,"code":413,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"greet();\n\nfunction greet() {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n\nvar anonymousGreet = function() {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n\nanonymousGreet();\n",[52,415,416,422,426,434,446,450,455,468,481,486,491],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,417,418,420],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,419,295],{"class":164},[55,421,308],{"class":65},[55,423,424],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,425,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},[55,427,428,430,432],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,429,258],{"class":61},[55,431,261],{"class":164},[55,433,264],{"class":65},[55,435,436,438,440,442,444],{"class":57,"line":325},[55,437,161],{"class":65},[55,439,165],{"class":164},[55,441,168],{"class":65},[55,443,275],{"class":171},[55,445,175],{"class":65},[55,447,448],{"class":57,"line":338},[55,449,282],{"class":65},[55,451,453],{"class":57,"line":452},6,[55,454,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},[55,456,458,460,462,464,466],{"class":57,"line":457},7,[55,459,62],{"class":61},[55,461,359],{"class":164},[55,463,362],{"class":61},[55,465,365],{"class":61},[55,467,264],{"class":65},[55,469,471,473,475,477,479],{"class":57,"line":470},8,[55,472,161],{"class":65},[55,474,165],{"class":164},[55,476,168],{"class":65},[55,478,275],{"class":171},[55,480,175],{"class":65},[55,482,484],{"class":57,"line":483},9,[55,485,282],{"class":65},[55,487,489],{"class":57,"line":488},10,[55,490,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},[55,492,494,496],{"class":57,"line":493},11,[55,495,402],{"class":164},[55,497,308],{"class":65},[17,499,500,501,503],{},"You'll notice the two aren't all that different. But the anonymous function we stored in ",[52,502,402],{}," only gets triggered once we tack on the parentheses.",[505,506,507],"blockquote",{},[17,508,509,512],{},[34,510,511],{},"Note","\nAn anonymous function is an expression.",[17,514,515],{},"And the biggest difference between a function statement and a function expression is this: a function statement just stuffs the function into memory. It only knows \"oh, there's a function here,\" then hoisting lifts it to the top, stores it in memory, and that's it.",[17,517,518],{},"But the function expression is different. It doesn't get hoisted to the top — only the variable gets hoisted, while the expression stays put where it was.",[17,520,521,522,525,526,529],{},"So what happens if we move ",[52,523,524],{},"anonymousGreet()"," above ",[52,527,528],{},"var anonymousGreet","?",[45,531,533],{"className":47,"code":532,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"anonymousGreet()\nvar anonymousGreet = function greet () {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n",[52,534,535,542,557,569],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,536,537,539],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,538,402],{"class":164},[55,540,541],{"class":65},"()\n",[55,543,544,546,548,550,552,554],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,545,62],{"class":61},[55,547,359],{"class":164},[55,549,362],{"class":61},[55,551,365],{"class":61},[55,553,261],{"class":164},[55,555,556],{"class":65}," () {\n",[55,558,559,561,563,565,567],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,560,161],{"class":65},[55,562,165],{"class":164},[55,564,168],{"class":65},[55,566,275],{"class":171},[55,568,175],{"class":65},[55,570,571],{"class":57,"line":325},[55,572,282],{"class":65},[17,574,575],{},"Now stop and think for a second: when the execution context is created, which two things get hoisted? Variables and functions. So what's the result going to be?",[17,577,578],{},[27,579],{"alt":402,"src":580},"https:\u002F\u002Fi.imgur.com\u002FyxRkc1r.png",[17,582,583,584,587,588,121],{},"We get ",[52,585,586],{},"TypeError: anonymousGreet is not a function",", not ",[52,589,590],{},"hi",[17,592,593],{},"So if you actually unpack what the code is doing, it looks like this. ↓",[45,595,597],{"className":47,"code":596,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"var anonymousGreet;\nanonymousGreet()\nanonymousGreet = function greet () {\n console.log('hi');\n};\n",[52,598,599,606,612,624,636],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,600,601,603],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,602,62],{"class":61},[55,604,605],{"class":65}," anonymousGreet;\n",[55,607,608,610],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,609,402],{"class":164},[55,611,541],{"class":65},[55,613,614,616,618,620,622],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,615,402],{"class":164},[55,617,362],{"class":61},[55,619,365],{"class":61},[55,621,261],{"class":164},[55,623,556],{"class":65},[55,625,626,628,630,632,634],{"class":57,"line":325},[55,627,161],{"class":65},[55,629,165],{"class":164},[55,631,168],{"class":65},[55,633,275],{"class":171},[55,635,175],{"class":65},[55,637,638],{"class":57,"line":338},[55,639,282],{"class":65},[17,641,642,643,645,646,648,649,651,652,654],{},"That's why you see ",[52,644,586],{}," — the variable ",[52,647,402],{}," gets hoisted to the top and assigned ",[52,650,120],{},", and ",[52,653,120],{}," itself can't be executed, so you get the error.",[17,656,657,658,661,662,664],{},"It's not until ",[52,659,660],{},"anonymousGreet ="," runs that ",[52,663,402],{}," gets correctly reassigned. So that gives us another takeaway.",[505,666,667],{},[17,668,669,671],{},[34,670,511],{},"\nFunction expressions don't get hoisted.",[17,673,674],{},"Let me stress one more time that a function is an object, which means you can do stuff like this:",[45,676,678],{"className":47,"code":677,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"function log(a){\n console.log(a);\n}\n\nlog(function() {\n console.log('hi');\n})\n",[52,679,680,695,704,708,712,722,734],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,681,682,684,687,689,692],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,683,258],{"class":61},[55,685,686],{"class":164}," log",[55,688,168],{"class":65},[55,690,76],{"class":691},"s_sBn",[55,693,694],{"class":65},"){\n",[55,696,697,699,701],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,698,161],{"class":65},[55,700,165],{"class":164},[55,702,703],{"class":65},"(a);\n",[55,705,706],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,707,181],{"class":65},[55,709,710],{"class":57,"line":325},[55,711,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},[55,713,714,716,718,720],{"class":57,"line":338},[55,715,165],{"class":164},[55,717,168],{"class":65},[55,719,258],{"class":61},[55,721,264],{"class":65},[55,723,724,726,728,730,732],{"class":57,"line":452},[55,725,161],{"class":65},[55,727,165],{"class":164},[55,729,168],{"class":65},[55,731,275],{"class":171},[55,733,175],{"class":65},[55,735,736],{"class":57,"line":457},[55,737,738],{"class":65},"})\n",[17,740,741,742,744],{},"So how do you get this to output ",[52,743,590],{},"? Just do this:",[45,746,748],{"className":47,"code":747,"language":49,"meta":50,"style":50},"function log(a){\n a();\n}\n\nlog(function() {\n console.log('hi');\n})\n",[52,749,750,762,769,773,777,787,799],{"__ignoreMap":50},[55,751,752,754,756,758,760],{"class":57,"line":58},[55,753,258],{"class":61},[55,755,686],{"class":164},[55,757,168],{"class":65},[55,759,76],{"class":691},[55,761,694],{"class":65},[55,763,764,767],{"class":57,"line":158},[55,765,766],{"class":164}," a",[55,768,308],{"class":65},[55,770,771],{"class":57,"line":178},[55,772,181],{"class":65},[55,774,775],{"class":57,"line":325},[55,776,314],{"emptyLinePlaceholder":313},[55,778,779,781,783,785],{"class":57,"line":338},[55,780,165],{"class":164},[55,782,168],{"class":65},[55,784,258],{"class":61},[55,786,264],{"class":65},[55,788,789,791,793,795,797],{"class":57,"line":452},[55,790,161],{"class":65},[55,792,165],{"class":164},[55,794,168],{"class":65},[55,796,275],{"class":171},[55,798,175],{"class":65},[55,800,801],{"class":57,"line":457},[55,802,738],{"class":65},[12,804,806],{"id":805},"source","Source",[17,808,809],{},[76,810,814],{"href":811,"rel":812},"https:\u002F\u002Fwww.udemy.com\u002Fjavascriptjs\u002F",[813],"nofollow","JavaScript Full Guide: Conquering the Weird Parts of JS",[816,817,818],"style",{},"html pre.shiki code .sWyjQ, html code.shiki .sWyjQ{--shiki-default:#FF9492}html pre.shiki code .sMAXC, html code.shiki .sMAXC{--shiki-default:#F0F3F6}html .default .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html .shiki span {color: var(--shiki-default);background: var(--shiki-default-bg);font-style: var(--shiki-default-font-style);font-weight: var(--shiki-default-font-weight);text-decoration: var(--shiki-default-text-decoration);}html pre.shiki code .sCcAr, html code.shiki .sCcAr{--shiki-default:#91CBFF}html pre.shiki code .sj_SG, html code.shiki .sj_SG{--shiki-default:#DBB7FF}html pre.shiki code .sTRMh, html code.shiki .sTRMh{--shiki-default:#ADDCFF}html pre.shiki code .s_sBn, html code.shiki .s_sBn{--shiki-default:#FFB757}",{"title":50,"searchDepth":158,"depth":158,"links":820},[821,822,823,824,825,826],{"id":14,"depth":158,"text":15},{"id":22,"depth":158,"text":23},{"id":130,"depth":158,"text":131},{"id":244,"depth":158,"text":245},{"id":343,"depth":158,"text":344},{"id":805,"depth":158,"text":806},"JsWeirdWorld","2019-05-18 21:13:00","Last chapter we figured out that functions are just objects. Now we're going to use that idea to do some genuinely fun and powerful stuff. But before we get there, we need to understand the difference between function statements and function expressions — and why one gets hoisted and the other doesn't.","md","en",{},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions","4",{"title":6,"description":829},false,"en\u002FJsWeirdWorld\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions",[839,814],"JavaScript",null,"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-27-function-statements-vs-expressions\u002F","CmYJT8pnl9hHjZr2eavTL1hngsutpLOtyRrCWa3ROB8",{"newer":844,"older":848},{"url":845,"title":846,"date":847},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F19\u002Fjs-weird-world-28-pass-by-value-vs-reference\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.28 A Quick Reminder: Pass by Value vs Pass by Reference","2019-05-19 12:13:00",{"url":849,"title":850,"date":851},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F18\u002Fjs-weird-world-26-functions-are-objects\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.26 Functions Are Just Objects","2019-05-18 20:13:00",[853,858,863],{"url":854,"title":855,"date":856,"readingMinutes":857},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F27\u002Fjs-weird-world-bonus-closures\u002F","[JS Weird World] Bonus: Closures, One More Time","2019-05-27 13:50:04","5",{"url":859,"title":860,"date":861,"readingMinutes":862},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-68-the-end-is-a-new-beginning\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.68 Wrapping Up the Weird Parts of JavaScript","2019-05-25 16:36:00","1",{"url":864,"title":865,"date":866,"readingMinutes":867},"\u002Fen\u002Fjsweirdworld\u002F2019\u002F05\u002F25\u002Fjs-weird-world-67-adding-jquery-support\u002F","[JS Weird World] No.67 Adding jQuery Support to Our Mini Framework","2019-05-25 16:19:00","2",1784010279415]